# The Complaint That Files Itself: Building a Self-Reporting Ops Engine for Banking

A client complaint about a failed AML verification and a client complaint about a slow SFTP upload look almost identical in a shared inbox. They are not the same problem. One is a compliance clock. The other is an engineering ticket. Most ops teams still triage both the same way — a person reads, decides, forwards, and hopes the right team sees it before the client gives up.

That gap between *"a client raised an issue"* and *"the right person is acting on it"* is where churn and compliance exposure actually live. I wanted to know if that gap could be closed automatically — not with more headcount, not with a new CRM, but with a small, focused loop of classification and action.

**The result was the ACR Framework — Ask, Check, Recommend — and it now runs client feedback through classification, escalation, and live conversational status reporting, with almost no human triage required.**

---

## What It Actually Does

- **Ask** — every piece of incoming feedback is read and classified: AML-Compliance, Tech-Infrastructure, or General Service
- **Check** — category maps to business priority (AML → P1, Tech → P2, General → P3), checked against SLA time thresholds
- **Recommend** — P1/P2 cases trigger an automatic, formatted alert to the right team, with a clear next action, seconds after the feedback lands
- A fourth capability sits on top of the loop: an ops manager can simply **ask** the system, in plain English, *"how many P1 cases are open right now?"* — and get a real, current answer.

That's the whole business case in one sentence: **feedback that classifies, escalates, and reports on itself.**

On the 100-row synthetic dataset this runs against, that comes out to **19 AML-Compliance (P1), 30 Tech-Infrastructure (P2), and 51 General Service (P3) cases — 49 of which trigger an automatic escalation digest.** Every one of those numbers reconciles exactly at every stage of the pipeline; nothing is estimated.

---

## The Build, Briefly

The pipeline runs on **n8n** — classification, priority logic, and SLA-aware Gmail alerts, all logged to a single source of truth. On top of that sits **Dify**, a conversational layer that answers ops questions by calling a live n8n webhook, not a static report.

That second half is worth a beat, because it's where the interesting decisions were.

**I tried the obvious approach first — load classified data into Dify's knowledge base and let semantic search answer questions.** It broke immediately on the one question that mattered most: *"how many."* Semantic search finds relevant text. It doesn't count rows. For a system whose entire value is trustworthy numbers, that failure mode was disqualifying, not a tuning problem.

**The fix was a live webhook instead of a static upload.** n8n computes exact counts on demand; Dify calls it fresh, every question, every time. No staleness, no approximation, ever.

**And a fair challenge I got early on: if n8n can compute everything, why bring in a second tool at all?** Because orchestration and conversation are different jobs. n8n has no native multi-turn memory and no natural-language reasoning over a follow-up question like *"what about the rest of the cases?"* Dify does that one thing well, while staying completely decoupled from the business logic, which never leaves n8n. Splitting the two made each side simpler — not redundant.

